[[Image:Soxhlet extractor.svg|thumb|200px|Soxhlet extractor (with condenser above and flask below)]]

===Etymology===
Invented in 1879 by Franz von Soxhlet.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈsɒkslət ɪkˌstɹæktə/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|head=[[w:Franz von Soxhlet|Soxhlet]] [[extractor]]}}

# {{lb|en|chemistry}} A piece of [[laboratory]] [[apparatus]] consisting of a glass [[reservoir]] that sits over a lower [[flask]] (containing a boiling [[solvent]]) and under a [[condenser]]; a sample contained in a paper [[thimble]] is placed in the reservoir and soluble materials are continually extracted by the warm solvent and transferred to the lower flask via a [[siphon]].
#* '''2006''', Thomas Pynchon, ''Against the Day'', Vintage 2007, p. 264:
#*: Amid a gleaming clutter of burners and spectroscopes, funnels and flasks, centrifugal and '''Soxhlet extractors''' {{...}}, serious girls with their hair in snoods entered numbers into log books

